# NSHostingView width must be set before rebuildHostingView

When an NSView wrapper creates an NSHostingView from a SwiftUI view, the SwiftUI view captures its initial property values at creation time. Changing properties on the parent NSView after the fact has NO effect on the SwiftUI content unless `rebuildHostingView()` is called again.

**Why:** On 2026-04-02, the file extract preview image was stuck at ~376px wide in a ~1400px container. Root cause: `FilePreviewOverlayView.init()` set `currentContainerWidth = 400` (default), called `rebuildHostingView()` which froze that value into the SwiftUI `FilePreviewContent(containerWidth: 400)`. The correct width was assigned AFTER init at line 6972, but without a rebuild. The SwiftUI view never saw the real width. This also caused height reservation mismatch -- `heightForData` used the correct width (1400) while the SwiftUI content rendered at 400pt.

**How to apply:**
1. **Always pass `containerWidth` (or equivalent) to init** so `rebuildHostingView()` uses the correct value from the start.
2. **For existing overlays, detect width changes and trigger rebuild:** `let widthChanged = abs(overlay.currentContainerWidth - newWidth) > 1; if widthChanged { overlay.rebuildHostingView() }`
3. **This applies to ALL NSView + NSHostingView overlays** in the editor (code blocks, callouts, tables, tabs, file previews). Any overlay that needs to respond to container width changes must rebuild on width change, not just on mode/data change.
4. **Never assume setting a property on the NSView propagates to SwiftUI.** `let` properties, non-`@Observable` values, and non-`@Binding` values are frozen at NSHostingView creation time.
